In this frenzy for scaling, I think we have become numb to just how large these numbers have become. 

I'm not making the bull or bear case, but I've found myself pointing out this simple observation to people: if OpenAI is indeed able to achieve their stated business model and execute on this model scaling through 2029 (per reporting by The Information), OpenAI will be eighteen times more capital dependent than the average tech megacap, and seven times more capital dependent than the runner up (Uber).

Capital dependency can be a wonderful attribute in a monopolistic or oligopolistic industry (see Buffett-BNSF...i.e. if I'm reasonably sure ever $1 of capex will pay off 10c, I'm happy to spend). This capex gambit CAN pay off in tech (Uber and Tesla eventually reached sufficient scale and fixed their unit economics), but capital dependency in a vacuum, certainly without regulated economics, is an incredibly risky business strategy (see WeWork). And this level of capital intensity in tech is risky (particularly given competition against well-funded peers).

I personally don't think this is bad news for AI as a tool. All of this capex today has created an incredible consumer surplus by giving us this magical tool (LLMs) that is really awesome. But for the galaxy brains betting on capexing our way into the singularity with $100bn+ training clusters, I may push back. Historically, AI winters have been driven the fundamental reality of hype bubbles bursting and funding cycles drying up. 

$100bn+ clusters *probably* aren't going to happen for the very simple capitalistic reason that *eventually*, even in the race for digital god, underlying investors will require a return on that capital. Investors in public tech companies tend to give the companies a longer leash for capex projects, but as we saw with the *metaverse capex vigilantes* at META, the tides can turn quickly. Will we see *training capex vigilantes* well before we get to $100bn clusters? I don't know, but if LLM capabilities continue to asymptote, probably.

Whenever you control the price of something, either artificially inflating it (NVDA/sp500) or suppressing it (interest rates, let‚Äôs focus on something other than PM‚Äôs for the moment to illustrate) you get imbalances in the economy. With rates, everybody loaded up on credit, as we‚Äôve seen, making it impossible to raise rates enough to meaningfully fight inflation, and making home prices unaffordable, and enabling the federal government to spend and grow way more than it should, among other effects. With a massively overvalued sp500/NVDA you get absurd amounts of capital misallocation. With silver, if you‚Äôll grant the assumption, the decades long price suppression signaled to the market that there was plenty of silver relative to demand, which in fact there wasn‚Äôt. This impacts miner‚Äôs incentive to find more metal. If the market had been provided with a true silver price signal, generally there wouldn‚Äôt be supply/demand imbalances. I‚Äôm sure you understand all of this, but it‚Äôs also the answer to your question, how does it hurt the public? - silver will reprice dramatically higher, which is why we‚Äôre all focused on it as investors, as those imbalances are corrected, forcing a repricing of end products that use silver. Interest rate suppression is more broadly negatively impactful to the public than the price of silver obviously, and those effects have been and will continue to be profound. Said simply, price controls hurt the public in the long run by signaling that there is ample supply of something that there isn‚Äôt ample supply of, leading to severe supply deficits in the end.

What is NVIDIA‚Äôs Lepton, and what does it mean for Nebius?

Lepton is a new service from $NVDA that helps companies quickly locate available GPUs across different cloud and data center providers. 

Instead of checking multiple vendors manually, users search once, choose the hardware and region they need, and Lepton shows which provider can deliver that compute power immediately.

Think of it like a travel aggregator, but for compute. Just like how Expedia shows you flights or hotels from multiple airlines and providers, Lepton routes you to whichever cloud has the GPUs you need, available now.

Why did NVIDIA step back from DGX Cloud?

DGX Cloud was an NVIDIA-branded, customer-facing service delivered on partner clouds (not NVIDIA-owned data centers). 

NVIDIA has de-emphasized it in favor of Lepton to avoid channel conflict with their customers and to double down on higher-margin strengths: GPUs, systems, and software. 

Lepton keeps developers on NVIDIA‚Äôs stack while letting providers win the workload, a cleaner, partner-friendly model.

Why would companies use Lepton?

Because in the world of AI, timing and configuration matter. Demand for GPUs often exceeds supply, especially for cutting-edge models, and waiting weeks for hardware can delay projects.

Lepton helps users:
‚Ä¢  Find GPUs available now
‚Ä¢  Choose based on performance, price, location, and data compliance
‚Ä¢  Access advanced setups like NVLink-based systems or specialized power/networking configurations

If your usual cloud has what you need, go there. If not, Lepton helps you find a provider who does‚Äîfast.

What does NVIDIA gain?

NVIDIA already dominates AI infrastructure with its GPUs, servers (like DGX), and software stack (CUDA, Triton, NIM). Now, with Lepton, it owns a new layer: the demand funnel‚Äîthe place where GPU buyers start their search.

This means NVIDIA benefits no matter which cloud a customer ends up choosing. With Lepton, Nvidia is not just making the GPUs. It‚Äôs shaping how they‚Äôre discovered and deployed.

What‚Äôs in it for cloud providers?

Lepton helps cloud providers:
‚Ä¢  Fill idle GPU capacity faster
‚Ä¢  Attract high-intent customers without marketing spend
‚Ä¢  Stand out on service, performance, and pricing

The trade-off? More price and performance transparency. Providers will face tougher comparisons, and will need to compete on:
‚Ä¢  Energy efficiency
‚Ä¢  Networking speed
‚Ä¢  Regional compliance
‚Ä¢  Support quality
‚Ä¢  Managed services

What does this mean for Nebius?

For Nebius, Lepton could be both a distribution channel and a visibility boost‚Äîa top-of-funnel that brings short-term jobs that might convert into long-term client relationships.

Importantly, Nebius is already well-positioned:

‚òëÔ∏è Custom-designed racks for GPU performance
‚òëÔ∏è Full-stack infrastructure: hardware + orchestration software
‚òëÔ∏è Energy-efficient data centers with a sustainability focus
‚òëÔ∏è AI tools and managed services ecosystem
‚òëÔ∏è Presence across EU, UK, U.S., and the Middle East

These differentiators matter, especially in a Lepton-driven world where buyers compare providers side by side.

Bigger Picture

Some analysts expect AI inference demand to outpace supply through 2030 and beyond, as AI extends from enterprise use to everyday life.

If that holds true, Lepton may become less about competition, and more about optimizing resource allocation across NVIDIA‚Äôs ecosystem‚Äîrouting workloads where there‚Äôs capacity, not creating price wars.

Bottom Line

Lepton isn‚Äôt just a compute marketplace, it‚Äôs $NVDA reinforcing its central role in AI infrastructure.

And for companies like $NBIS, it‚Äôs a new opportunity to:
‚Ä¢  Get discovered by high-intent buyers
‚Ä¢  Build trust through differentiated performance and service
‚Ä¢  Convert short-term demand into long-term business

In a world where compute is currency, Lepton is the new exchange‚Äîand $NBIS is well positioned to be part of it.

üö® Fresh from the Fed's September 17, 2025 FOMC meeting: 

The latest Summary of Economic Projections (SEP) paints a resilient picture for the US economy, with some upward revisions in growth and tweaks to the rate path. 

They also delivered a 25bp rate cut today, bringing the federal funds target to 4.00%-4.25%. 

üëâ Here's a breakdown of the key medians vs. June 2025 projections:

1Ô∏è‚É£ GDP Growth (Q4/Q4 % change):
- 2025: 1.6% (‚Üë from 1.4% in June) ‚Äì Stronger outlook amid solid consumer spending.
- 2026: 1.8% (‚Üë from 1.6%) ‚Äì Continued momentum.
- Longer run: 1.8% (unchanged).

2Ô∏è‚É£Unemployment Rate (%):
- 2025: 4.5% (unchanged from June) ‚Äì Steady labor market.
- 2026: 4.4% (‚Üì from 4.5%) ‚Äì Slight improvement expected.
- Longer run: 4.2% (unchanged).

3Ô∏è‚É£ PCE Inflation (%):
- 2025: 3.0% (unchanged) ‚Äì Still above target but stable.
- 2026: 2.6% (‚Üë from 2.4%) ‚Äì Modest upward tick, possibly due to persistent services inflation.
- Longer run: 2.0% (unchanged) ‚Äì Back to mandate.

4Ô∏è‚É£ Core PCE Inflation (%):
- 2025: 3.1% (unchanged).
- 2026: 2.6% (‚Üë from 2.4%).

5Ô∏è‚É£ Federal Funds Rate (% ‚Äì end of year):
- 2025: 3.6% (‚Üì from 3.9%) ‚Äì Dot plot now signals TWO more 25bp cuts this year (up from one in June), easing to ~3.50%-3.75%.
- 2026: 3.4% (‚Üì from 3.6%) ‚Äì Further gradual cuts.
- Longer run: 3.0% (unchanged).

üéØ Overall, the Fed sees a "soft landing" intact: brighter growth, stable jobs, but inflation cooling slower than hoped. Markets are pricing in more easing ahead.

üìù Worth noting: If future data updates reveal lower-than-expected inflation alongside higher unemployment, it could provide justification for even more aggressive rate cuts beyond the two additional 25bp reductions forecasted before year-end.

Despite Powell's conservative speech, if inflation doesn't go higher than Fed's forecast, I would expect a bullish continuation trend until the end of the year.

Watched @realMeetKevin‚Äôs video on $NVDA  / $CRWV deal.

Nvidia is agreeing to lease compute from Coreweave in case they aren‚Äôt able to find other customers.

Kevin‚Äôs argument is that this is bearish because it‚Äôs a sign that NVDA/CRWV see softening demand for data centers and NVDA wants to protect their current demand for GPUs and CRWV wants to limit their risk in this scenario.

My view is the opposite. Nvidia is effectively writing puts against their GPUs because they think it‚Äôs unlikely that they go unleased. The agreement however makes it easier for Coreweave to get financing and for companies to trust that the demand will continue. In the short run this increases demand for GPUs, which isn‚Äôt particularly important since Nvidia‚Äôs GPU demand is already sky high, but more importantly it increases tech companies‚Äô willingness to invest in new data center infrastructure which will increase demand for GPUs longer term.

If you take the view Kevin does Nvidia‚Äôs deal doesn‚Äôt really make sense from their standpoint because it will just end up costing them long term, and they‚Äôre making the agreement at a time when they don‚Äôt need a short term boost in share price.

If on the other hand you view this as a sign that they see demand continuing and they want to signal to tech companies to keep building out data center infrastructure it makes perfect sense.

$PFSA : Real-time biochemistry data powered by $NVDA
Proprietary Tissue-Integrated Sensor Platform Profusa's core technology, the injectable hydrogel biosensor, is a fundamental advancement in continuous monitoring. The company's primary innovation is its ability to overcome the foreign body response (FBR), the body's defensive reaction to foreign material. This FBR is a significant biological barrier that has historically limited the long-term functionality of most implantable sensors by causing biofouling and fibrous encapsulation. In contrast, Profusa's "smart gel" is designed to mimic the body's natural tissues, allowing the sensor to become fully integrated. This unique bioengineering approach allows for continuous, long-lasting data collection without the inflammation or rejection that plagues traditional devices.
This capability provides a substantial competitive advantage. While established competitors like Dexcom and Abbott have highly successful percutaneous sensors, their products are still susceptible to biofouling and require frequent replacement, typically within a few weeks. The company's ability to offer months of functionality from a single injection‚Äîwith its glucose sensor demonstrating a duration of up to nine months in studies ‚Äîimproves patient convenience and comfort while creating a powerful differentiator in the market. The solution to the FBR is not merely a technical detail; it is the core of the company's value proposition, representing a critical, hard-won competitive moat that could capture market share from patients seeking longer-duration solutions

CoreWeave-NVIDIA $6.3 Billion Deal: Strategic Impact Analysis for $GLXY and Other GW Leasers

The announcement of the $6.3 billion cloud capacity agreement between $CRWV and $NVDA represents a transformative development in the AI infrastructure landscape that significantly benefits CoreWeave's key partners, particularly Galaxy Digital Holdings $GLXY. Alongside the $ORCL RPO numbers that dropped last week - all this deal does is confirm just how much demand there is for AI and AI infrastructure moving forward. It not only solidifies CoreWeave's position as a dominant AI cloud provider but also creates substantial downstream value for its infrastructure partners.

The $NVDA - $CRWV agreement establishes a comprehensive capacity purchase guarantee valued initially at $6.3 billion, extending through April 13, 2032. Under this arrangement, $NVDA commits to purchasing any unused cloud computing capacity that $CRWV cannot sell to its direct customers, effectively providing a revenue floor for the AI cloud provider's operations. This guarantee mechanism transforms $CRWV's business model from demand-dependent to revenue-assured, eliminating capacity utilization risk across its expanding data center network.

$CRWV's financial trajectory leading to this deal demonstrates explosive growth momentum. The company's quarterly revenue surged from $116 million in Q4 2023 to $1.21 billion in Q2 2025, representing a remarkable 542.8% year-over-year increase. Operating at an annualized revenue run rate of $4.85 billion, the $6.3 billion $NVDA deal represents approximately 130% of $CRWV's current annual revenue capacity, highlighting the transformative scale of this partnership.

$GLXY emerges as one of the greatest beneficiary of this $NVDA - $CRWV deal through its extensive partnership via the Helios data center campus transformation. With 800 MW already signed to $CRWV, this new partnership essentially guarantees the leasing of the GPU clusters within the Helios facility throughout 2032. What once was a demand-driven game can now be confirmed through the backing of $NVDA's financials.

$GLXY Digital's Helios facility represents the company's flagship AI and high-performance computing data center campus in West Texas, developed through a $1.75 billion total investment including a $1.4 billion debt facility. Under the 15-year lease agreement with $CRWV, $GLXY expects to generate over $1 billion in annual revenue, totaling approximately $15 billion across the contract duration.

The $NVDA deal significantly de-risks $GLXY's Helios investment by ensuring $CRWV maintains stable cash flows to meet its lease obligations. With $NVDA guaranteeing to purchase unused $CRWV capacity, $GLXY's revenue streams become effectively backstopped by $NVDA's financial strength, creating an additional layer of payment security for the infrastructure provider.

I think single names should be everyone‚Äôs focus! Not ‚Äúown momentum‚Äù. 

But in all seriousness‚Ä¶Here is how I draw the lines on a single name using NVDA year to date‚Ä¶. First pick the LENS. Versus SPY, versus large cap growth GLD/ QQQ, versus semis SMH, versus an AI basket like MSXXAIB, and versus direct peers. Now do the naive excess returns just to build intuition. NVDA 30 percent over SPY 13 percent gives plus 17. Over QQQ 16 percent gives plus 14. Over SMH 27 percent gives plus 3. Versus MSXXAIB 56 percent gives -26. Versus AMD 33 percent gives -3. Versus AVGO 57 percent gives -27. Versus MRVL  -38 percent gives +68. Those are not alpha yet, they are context. True single name alpha comes only after removing the risks you knowingly took. That means run a rolling regression of NVDA on your chosen benchmark plus a factor set such as market, size, value, quality, momentum, liquidity, and an explicit semis and AI flow factor, subtract costs and borrow, and then examine the alpha path. If the residual is small versus SMH or MSXXAIB, you mostly owned the factor. If the residual is persistent with a healthy information ratio and sensible drawdown elasticity, you likely had selection or timing skill. Factor timing can count as alpha here if you systematically leaned into or away from the AI and semis factors ahead of the move and that edge remains after neutralization and costs. My rule for single names. State the benchmark up front. Report beta and factor loadings. Show alpha in percent and its volatility and the t statistic. Attribute selection versus timing versus execution. If it disappears when neutralized, scaled, or costed, it was not alpha. If it persists with clean attribution, realistic capacity, and a path you can underwrite, that is the craft

In contrast, NVIDIA A800 has 80GB of graphics memory and a bandwidth of 400GB/s; Huawei Shengteng 910B has 64GB of graphics memory and a bandwidth of 900GB/s.

Industry insiders pointed out that this data disclosure reflects that domestic computing chips are gradually narrowing the gap with leading international manufacturers. Especially in terms of high-bandwidth storage and PCIe 5.0 interface, Pingtouge chips show strong competitiveness, providing more options for China's autonomous computing power deployment in AI large models and data centers.
